<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,222,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,505,366,391]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[516,699,366,391]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scypheus">
<emphasis box="[516,699,366,391]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Anolis scypheus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to western Amazonia, occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1261,1329,366,391]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(state of Amazonas), 
<collectingCountry box="[293,406,402,427]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[418,513,402,427]" name="Ecuador" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[573,625,403,426]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[640,709,402,427]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,419,1309]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,409,1318]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of examined material of Anolis planiceps, A. scypheus and A. tandai." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/234986/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[693,709,402,427]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[762,833,402,427]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is known only from the Japurá river basin, state of Amazonas. 
<taxonomicName box="[283,462,438,463]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scypheus">
<emphasis box="[283,462,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Anolis scypheus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is predominantly terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits primary and secondary forests, where it is usually found on the ground, and occasionally on lower vegetation (tree trunks, fallen trunks, lianas and shrubs), lower than 
<number box="[373,387,511,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
meters high (
<bibRefCitation author="Duellman" box="[540,718,510,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Duellman, W. E. (1978) The biology of an equatorial herpetofauna in Amazonian Ecuador. Miscellaneous Publications, Museum of Natural History of University of Kansas, 65, 1 - 352." type="journal article" year="1978">
Duellman 
<number box="[659,718,511,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1978.0">1978</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; Vitt &amp; Zani 
<number box="[866,926,510,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1996.0">1996</number>
b,c; 
<bibRefCitation author="Whitworth" box="[970,1269,510,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Whitworth, A. &amp; Beirne, C. (2011) Reptiles of the Yachana Reserve. Global Vision International, Exeter, 127 pp." type="book" year="2011">
Whitworth &amp; Beirne 
<number box="[1209,1269,511,535]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
